summary:
North Korea tested a high-thrust solid-fuel engine producing 2,500 kilonewtons, overseen by Kim Jong-un. The engine can power ICBMs capable of striking global targets including the U.S. mainland. This follows prior tests with lower thrust output. Kim Jong-un described it as enhancing North Korea's strategic power. Analysts assess potential for multiple warheads on such missiles.

In the Middle East, updated reports state an Iranian strike injured two dozen U.S. troops at Saudi Prince Sultan Air Base. U.S. Marines deployed to the region as Houthis fired a missile at Israel from Yemen. Iranian Revolutionary Guards targeted aluminum facilities in Bahrain and the UAE, wounding two employees at Aluminium Bahrain, a major global producer. Affected workers received treatment, with disruptions to regional energy and industry. An Israeli military strike in southern Lebanon killed three journalists, including one from Hezbollah-linked Al Manar TV whom Israel accuses of operative ties. Lebanon condemned the attack.

Drone strikes killed 22 civilians including an infant at a North Darfur market and six at a North Kordofan truck in Sudan, injuring 17 others total as the civil war approaches its fourth year. The Sudanese army and Rapid Support Forces face blame. NATO initiated coordinated action after suspected sabotage severed another Baltic Sea cable, targeting critical infrastructure. Ukraine secured air defense supply deals with Qatar and Saudi Arabia during a Middle East visit. A U.S. Senate agreement to fund the Department of Homeland Security collapsed, risking a partial government shutdown affecting border security and disaster response. NASA introduced the Artemis 2 crew—commander Reid Wiseman, pilot Victor Glover, specialists Christina Koch and Jeremy Hansen—for a 2026 lunar orbit mission, the first in 52 years, with Australia providing communications support."}
